{"format": "tiptap/v1", "updatedAt": "2026-06-22T12:15:04.422Z", "doc": {"type": "doc", "content": [{"type": "image", "attrs": {"src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,", "alt": "Gradient Clipping — concept overview"}}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "What Gradient Clipping Is"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Gradient clipping"}, {"type": "text", "text": " is a technique used to prevent "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "exploding gradients"}, {"type": "text", "text": " during neural network training by capping the size of gradients before the weight update step. In plain terms, if the gradient becomes too large, it is rescaled so training stays stable."}]}, {"type": "horizontalRule"}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Why It Matters"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "In deep networks and recurrent models, gradients can grow so large that the optimizer takes huge updates and the model becomes unstable or diverges. Gradient clipping keeps training in a safe range, which helps the model keep learning instead of “blowing up”."}]}, {"type": "horizontalRule"}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "How It Works"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "The basic idea is simple: compute the gradient normally, then check whether its magnitude exceeds a chosen threshold. If it does, scale the whole gradient vector down so its norm is at most that threshold."}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "A common form is "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "clipping by norm"}, {"type": "text", "text": ":"}]}, {"type": "blockMath", "attrs": {"latex": "g \\leftarrow c \\cdot \\frac{g}{\\|g\\|}"}}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "when "}, {"type": "inlineMath", "attrs": {"latex": "\\|g\\| \\ge c"}}, {"type": "text", "text": ", where "}, {"type": "inlineMath", "attrs": {"latex": "g"}}, {"type": "text", "text": " is the gradient and "}, {"type": "inlineMath", "attrs": {"latex": "c"}}, {"type": "text", "text": " is the clipping threshold. If the gradient is already small enough, nothing changes."}]}, {"type": "horizontalRule"}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Common Types"}]}, {"type": "table", "content": [{"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableHeader", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Type"}]}]}, {"type": "tableHeader", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "What it does"}]}]}, {"type": "tableHeader", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Effect"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Clip by value"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Caps each gradient element to a min/max range"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Simple, but can distort direction"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Clip by norm"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Rescales the whole gradient vector if its norm is too large"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Preserves direction better"}]}]}]}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Clipping by norm is usually preferred because it reduces the magnitude while keeping the gradient’s overall direction more intact."}]}, {"type": "horizontalRule"}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Why It Helps in Generative AI"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Gradient clipping is especially useful in "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "RNNs, LSTMs, GRUs, and Transformers"}, {"type": "text", "text": ", where backpropagation can produce unstable gradient spikes. In generative AI, this helps models train on long sequences without sudden divergence or numerical overflow."}]}, {"type": "horizontalRule"}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Trade-offs"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Gradient clipping does "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "not"}, {"type": "text", "text": " fix vanishing gradients; it mainly addresses exploding gradients. If the threshold is set too low, it can also make learning too conservative by shrinking updates excessively."}]}, {"type": "horizontalRule"}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Mental Model"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Think of gradient clipping like a "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "speed limiter"}, {"type": "text", "text": " on a car. If training starts accelerating too fast, the limiter keeps the update from becoming dangerous, so the model stays on the road instead of crashing."}]}, {"type": "horizontalRule"}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Key Takeaways"}]}, {"type": "bulletList", "content": [{"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Gradient clipping prevents "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "exploding gradients"}, {"type": "text", "text": " by limiting gradient size before the optimizer step."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "A common method is "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "clipping by norm"}, {"type": "text", "text": ", which rescales the whole gradient vector."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "It is widely used in "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "recurrent networks and Transformers"}, {"type": "text", "text": " to stabilize training."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "It helps avoid unstable updates, divergence, and numerical overflow."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "It does "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "not"}, {"type": "text", "text": " solve vanishing gradients; it specifically targets gradients that are too large."}]}]}]}]}}